ed-on--003.jpg"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/media/2013/oct/07/media-briefing-monday-7-october","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/media/2013/oct/07/media-briefing-monday-7-october","sectionName":"Media"},{"webTitle":"Made in Japan: the new tool to mitigate climate change","webPublicationDate":"2013-10-03T10:07:00Z","sectionId":"global-development-professionals-network","id":"global-development-professionals-network/2013/oct/03/climate-change-tool-japan","fields":{"body":"<p>The government of Japan has developed the <a href=\"http://climate-l.iisd.org/news/japan-launches-joint-crediting-mechanism/\">joint credit mechanism </a>(JCM) to mitigate climate change and help developing countries achieve low-carbon growth by mobilising technology, markets and finance. Japan is also pushing for widespread use of advanced low-carbon technologies and products in various fields.</p><p>The JCM aims to facilitate diffusion of leading low-carbon technologies, products, systems, services, and infrastructure as well as implementation of mitigation actions, and contribute to sustainable development of developing countries. It also aims to evaluate reduction in greenhouse gas emission levels in a quantitative manner, by applying measurement, reporting and verification methodologies, and using them to achieve Japan's emissions reduction target.</p><p>The JCM will also contribute to the <a href=\"http://unfccc.int/2860.php\">United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change</a> objective by facilitating global actions for cutting emissions and complementing the clean development mechanism under the <a href=\"http://unfccc.int/kyoto_protocol/items/2830.php\">Kyoto protocol</a>.  For example, a JCM project in Mongolia plans to replace conventional coal-based boilers with new energy-efficient ones. Reducing coal use will not only contribute to mitigation of climate change but also improve economic efficiency and air quality. Such efforts are being driven by Japan's financial and technological support through the JCM.</p><p>Japan and a host country establish a joint committee to govern and operate the JCM. The committee develops and adopts rules and guidelines, registers projects, and issues JCM credits for greenhouse gas emission reductions or removals. The committee is also tasked to prevent JCM projects from being registered under any other international climate mitigation mechanisms, to avoid double counting on emission reductions.</p><p>Under the JCM, emission reductions are defined as the difference between \"reference emissions\" and project emissions.  The reference emissions are calculated below business-as-usual emissions, which represent plausible emissions in providing the same outputs or service level of the proposed JCM project in the host country. Together with applying default values for several parameters in calculating emission reductions, these approaches ensure a net decrease and/or avoidance of emissions while reducing the burden of measurement, and increasing transparency for calculating  emission reductions.</p><p>A growing number of countries are joining the JCM, which this year has entered into a new phase. After continuous efforts to develop the concept through several studies and discussions with partner countries, the JCM is now ready for the implementation.</p><p>In January, Mongolia signed a bilateral pact with Japan to implement JCM in capital Ulan Bator. Since then Bangladesh, Ethiopia, Kenya, Maldives, Vietnam and Laos have also joined JCM.</p><p>The government of Japan is strengthening its efforts to popularise JCM through demonstration of projects backed by financial investments in  advanced technologies, together with support for feasibility studies and capacity building in partner countries. The country is expecting JCM to start reducing emissions as it transfers technology to developing countries.</p><p><em><em>Yuji Mizuno is the director for international negotiations at the climate change policy division of the environment ministry of Japan. </em>For more information, visit the <a href=\"http://www.mmechanisms.org/e/\" title=\"\">New Mechanisms Information Platform</a></em></p><p><strong>This content is brought to you by <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/guardian-professional\">Guardian Professional</a>. To get more articles like this direct to your inbox, sign up free to become a member of the </strong><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/global-development-professionals-network\" title=\"\"><strong>Global Development Professionals Network</strong></a></p>","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Environment/Pix/columnists/2011/5/10/1305037155949/Japan-renewable-energy--S-003.jpg"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/global-development-professionals-network/2013/oct/03/climate-change-tool-japan","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/global-development-professionals-network/2013/oct/03/climate-change-tool-japan","sectionName":"Global Development Professionals Network"},{"webTitle":"Facebook or Google: which website rules the world?","webPublicationDate":"2013-10-03T08:00:00Z","sectionId":"news","id":"news/datablog/2013/oct/03/facebook-google-most-viewed-website-map","fields":{"body":"<p>We have reached the age of internet empires with just a handful of websites dominating internet traffic across the globe. </p><p><a href=\"http://www.oii.ox.ac.uk/people/?id=321\">Stefano De Sabbata</a> and <a href=\"http://www.oii.ox.ac.uk/people/graham/\">Dr Mark Graham</a> from the <a href=\"http://www.oii.ox.ac.uk/\">Oxford Internet Institute</a> have tried to show this with a map visualising each country's most popular website using a design that pays homage to the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Age_of_Empires\">Age of Empires</a> video game series.</p><p>You can click on the map below to zoom in and see the countries in detail. There is a key showing the websites featured at the bottom left of the map. </p><p><strong></strong></p><p>The researchers explain their methodology on their <a href=\"http://geography.oii.ox.ac.uk/2013/09/age-of-internet-empires/\">Information Geographies</a> blog:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>The map uses freely available data retrieved from <a href=\"http://www.alexa.com/\">Alexa</a> on August 12th, 2013. The company has provided website analytics since 1996. Alexa collects data from millions of internet users using one of over 25,000 different browser extensions, and the <a href=\"http://www.alexa.com/help/traffic-learn-more\">data used for this visualization</a> were calculated \"using a combination of the estimated average daily unique visitors to a site and the estimated number of pageviews on that site from users in that country over the past month\".</p><p>The data are visualised as a choropleth map, where the colour indicates each country's most visited website. Starting from the evident dominance of two companies (Google and Facebook), whose colours (red and blue, respectively) cover most of the map, we styled the illustration as an <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:British_colonies_1763-76_shepherd1923.PNG\">old colonial map</a>, and named it after the computer game series <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Age_of_Empires\">Age of Empires</a>.</p></blockquote><h2>The age of internet empires</h2><p>So Google and Facebook rule most of the world except Asia where local providers have managed to maintain their domination of the market. </p><p>The researchers point out that Google is the most visited website in the majority of European, North American and Oceanian countries while Facebook dominates in the Middle East, North Africa and most Spanish-speaking countries in South America.</p><p>The once dominant Yahoo! maintains a stronghold in Japan, where it is branded Yahoo Japan! (as a joint venture with Japanese company SoftBank) and also in Taiwan.</p><p>Unfortunately there are some countries missing from the map, as the researchers explain:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Alexa does not provide much information about countries in Sub-Saharan Africa. However, most countries that have a significant Internet population are covered. Kenya, Madagascar, Nigeria, and South Africa fall within the sphere of Google's empire, whereas Ghana, Senegal, and Sudan have been subsumed within Facebook's dominion.</p></blockquote><h2>Size is not everything</h2><p>The countries where Google is dominant contain half of the internet's whole population, with over one billion users. </p><p>Although the locations it dominates contain more landmass, Facebook loses out to Chinese search engine Baidu when it comes to total internet population.</p><p>To illustrate this discrepancy De Sabbata and Graham have also displayed the data on a map where countries are sized by internet population.</p><p><strong></strong></p><h2><strong>Find out more</strong></h2><p>• Contact us at <a href=\"mailto:data@guardian.co.uk\">data@theguardian.com</a><br />• Follow us <a href=\"http://twitter.com/guardiandata\">on Twitter</a><br />• Like us <a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/pages/Guardian-data/155291341187950\">on Facebook</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/page/2009/jun/17/1\">Get the A-Z of data</a></p>","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/10/2/1380710677156/Picture_96.png"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/news/datablog/2013/oct/03/facebook-google-most-viewed-website-map","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/news/datablog/2013/oct/03/facebook-google-most-viewed-website-map","sectionName":"News"},{"webTitle":"Five tips for healthcare companies entering emerging markets","webPublicationDate":"2013-10-02T18:15:00Z","sectionId":"sustainable-business","id":"sustainable-business/healthcare-investors-brics-emerging-markets","fields":{"body":"<p>There's no denying the critical need for healthcare investment in developing countries. Developing countries account for 80% of global deaths from chronic diseases, according to the <a href=\"https://www.wbginvestmentclimate.org/advisory-services/health/guide-for-investors-in-private-health-care-markets.cfm\">International Finance Corp (IFJ)</a>.<br /> <br />That need also spells a big market opportunity, as – in countries belonging to the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development – <a href=\"https://www.wbginvestmentclimate.org/advisory-services/health/guide-for-investors-in-private-health-care-markets.cfm\">healthcare markets have grown faster than GDP for decades</a>.<br /> <br />As Dimitri Drone, pharmaceutical and life sciences leader at <a href=\" http://www.pwc.com/us/en/index.jhtml\">PwC</a>, puts it: \"The US is 5% of the total global population. There's a whole lot of other people around the world that are coming up with some of the same ailments [as] the people in the US.\"<br /> <br />Until a few years ago, though, corporations didn't appear interested in tapping into that opportunity. While developing regions attracted some scattered for-profit medical services in the past, these were mostly mom-and-pop operations, and nonprofits shouldered the biggest load.</p><p>Now, industry observers say companies are putting significant amounts of money on the table – not only for Brazil, India and China, but also for Russia, Cambodia and African countries – for the first time.</p><p>\"It has only been in the last five years that people see that there is a profit to be made if you are invested in healthcare in Africa,\" said Nicole Spieker, program director at the PharmaAccess Foundation, at the <a href=\" http://socialcapitalmarkets.net/\">Social Capital Markets conference</a> in San Francisco last month. Before that, she said, \"the world really hasn't been investing in healthcare in Africa, even though the highest need is there.\"</p><p>GE Healthcare, which <a href=\"http://www.forbes.com/sites/greatspeculations/2012/03/21/ge-healthcares-india-center-is-a-model-of-its-emerging-markets-strategy/\">invests millions in research and development of medical equipment for emerging markets every year</a>, has posted <a href=\"http://seekingalpha.com/article/1447891-ge-healthcare-targets-growth-markets-and-new-technologies-to-drive-sales\">strong annual sales growth</a> in the last few years – reaching $18.3bn in 2012 – and profit of $726m in the second quarter (the latest reported) on revenue of $4.49bn. </p><p><a href=\"http://www.gsk.com/responsibility/health-for-all/investing-in-least-developed-countries.html\">GlaxoSmithKline</a> also has been plunking down millions annually, <a href=\"http://gpah.bsr.org/en/case-studies/view/strengthening-healthcare-systems-through-investment-in-community-health-wo\">reinvesting 20% of the profits generated in the world's least-developed countries into community healthcare programs</a> since 2009.</p><p>Aside from GE and GSK, global corporations such as Siemens Healthcare, Phillips Healthcare, Hewlett-Packard and others are tapping these growing markets, providing <a href=\"http://www.nextbillion.net/blogpost.aspx?blogid=2799\">medical equipment, healthcare clinics</a> and <a href=\"http://www.prweb.com/releases/healthcare-it-market/07/prweb10901029.htm\">healthcare IT</a>, including <a href=\"http://www.imsresearch.com/press-release/medical_grade_display_market_soars_as_demand_rises_in_disparate_regions\">display technology</a>.</p><h2>Healthcare privatization: potential and challenges</h2><p>What's spurring the growth? A <a href=\"http://www.thebostoncompany.com/assets/pdf/views-insights/Aug12_Global_Wealth_Creation_EMHealthCare.pdf\">rising middle class in emerging economies</a>, for one thing, and <a href=\"https://www.wbginvestmentclimate.org/advisory-services/health/upload/Opportunities-and-Trends-in-Investing-Guide_for_Investors_in_Private_Health_Care_in_Emerging_Markets.pdf \">increasing awareness that many governments don't have the resources to meet healthcare needs in developing countries</a>.</p><p>According to the IFJ report, private and out-of-pocket expenditures make up roughly 50% of total health spending in most developing countries – and far more in countries such as India, Nigeria, Georgia, Guatemala and Vietnam. In addition, more than 60% of women who gave birth in India, Cambodia, Nepal, Indonesia, Bangladesh, Rwanda, Kenya and Ethiopia delivered their babies in private medical facilities, according to surveys discussed in the report.</p><p>Private companies are seen favorably, compared to the public sector, says Peju Adenusi, executive director of the <a href=\"http://hygeiafoundation.org/\">Hygeia Foundation</a> in Nigeria.</p><p>\"Initially we had a lack of public health facilities\", she said. \"But along the line there was a breakdown in the healthcare delivery system, which made people look for an alternative and that alternative was the private sector.\"</p><p>That said, corporate investors also face significant challenges, including lower prices – and margins – leading to longer time horizons for returns. </p><p>\"Investors are skittish,\" Drone said. \"They can't wait to build a presence in an emerging market or a developing market, because that could take a decade or two or three decades to get there.\"</p><h2>Five factors to consider</h2><p>Here are five considerations for healthcare companies wanting to make their mark in emerging economies:</p><p><strong>The money is already in the can</strong><br /> <br />Most US corporations in this space already have a manufacturing or operations facility in place. A good chunk of that <a href=\"http://www.altiusdirectory.com/Business/offshore-manufacturing.html\">money has to stay overseas</a>, so it can make sense for businesses to use these extra funds to start a healthcare arm overseas rather than to use the money to spur stateside growth.</p><p>\"Many life sciences companies have manufacturing outside use and they hold intellectual property outside of the US. Many of these companies have made billions and billions of dollars and they have that cash on their balance sheet,\" Drone said. Another plus? Using the money to grow in emerging economies likely means lower taxes, he adds. </p><p>Many big companies will find that an <a href=\"http://www.trefis.com/stock/ge/articles/106396/ge-healthcare-looks-to-low-cost-solutions-for-emerging-markets/2012-03-05\">already-established tie</a> will make the entry much easier.<br /> <br /><strong>New opportunities require new ways of marketing</strong><br /> <br />Don't expect you can just run a commercial or put up billboards to market your product. Business as usual will not work in emerging countries.</p><p>\"Communicating with consumers is a lot different. There are a lot of regulations and people have been fined for pretty big amounts for their marketing practices,\" Drone said.</p><p><strong>Seek a helping hand</strong><br />Partnerships with NGOs can strengthen both the quality of the services you can provide and, potentially, profit.</p><p>\"There's a greater understanding with the donors that this is actually something that can help deal with the reduction in development aid that you see from European countries and others\", Spieker said.<br /> <br /><strong>Be patient</strong><br /> <br />\"It takes time to build up a whole system,\" Spieker said. \"You start by building quality of care and then there will be a demand for your healthcare. People get to know and trust the system and then they will come to rely on your services.\"<br /> <br /><strong>Price really matters</strong><br /> <br />It may seem obvious, but in emerging markets, you need to price to sell, not go for the highest price the market can bear. </p><p>\"In the past you could price your technology, your product in the US, on a level where you could make a handsome return on your R&amp;D investment, but you have to lower the price in emerging economies,\" Drone said. \"If you want to maximize the value of an asset, you have to go to more of a volume plan than a price plan.\" </p><p><em>Jennifer Inez Ward is a freelance writer and photographer in Oakland, California</em></p>","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/10/2/1380737141158/Daily-Life-In-Siem-Reap-005.jpg"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sustainable-business/healthcare-investors-brics-emerging-markets","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/sustainable-business/healthcare-investors-brics-emerging-markets","sectionName":"Guardian Sustainable Business"},{"webTitle":"Global development podcast: Big ideas for development after 2015 – transcript","webPublicationDate":"2013-10-02T10:43:34Z","sectionId":"global-development","id":"global-development/2013/oct/02/global-development-podcast-2015-transcript","fields":{"body":"<p><strong>HM:</strong> Hugh Muir</p><p><strong>AC:</strong> Alex Cobham</p><p><strong>BC:</strong> Barbara Crowther</p><p><strong>MK:</strong> Dr Musimbi Kanyoro</p><p><strong>LF:</strong> Liz Ford</p><p></p><p><strong>HM</strong> Hello and welcome to the Global development podcast. My name's Hugh Muir. Coming up, the millennium development goals, or MDGs, are up for renewal in 2015. Between now and then diplomats and activists from every country will talk long and hard about shaping new goals for the future. But before we go forward, let's look back: have the development goals achieved everything that was hoped for? And what about those targets? Even if we do agree new goals is that really the best way to achieve sustainable development? Today we'll hear from three big thinkers with big ideas about how about to build a better world. This is the Global development podcast from the Guardian. And with me in the studio today are Alex Cobham, research fellow at the Centre for Global Development; and Barbara Crowther, director of policy and public affairs at the Fairtrade Foundation. And in our New York office we have Dr Musimbi Kanyoro, president of the Global Fund for Women, and Liz Ford, deputy editor of Global development at the Guardian. Thank you all for joining us.</p><p>And, Liz, let me start with you before we get stuck into those big ideas, let's start with a little context. At the time of recording there's a big meeting at the United Nations, that's why you're there, apart from the obvious charms of New York of course, so tell us what's going on there?</p><p><strong>LF</strong> The UN has its development moment over the next three days, where we're expecting leaders to review where we're at with the MDGs, where we've got, what we need to do in the next two years to actually achieve the 2015 target. And then looking beyond that, what happens after 2015 – the next set of goals. And there have been discussions been going on all year. The UN have commissioned a high level panel co-chaired by David Cameron to come up with some kind of vision. And in their report in May they produced a draft set of 12 goals, which seemed to have sort of captured the imagination and seemed to be used quite readily at any kind of conversation, almost like these are the ideas for a new set of goals; but there still needs to be lots of discussion. And what we're expecting this week is to get some kind of idea about whether these goals are going to be universal, and for the UN to set in motion what's going to happen next, so the next two years there's key marker points about when deadlines are to come up with these ideas. And in a sense this is sort of the year of throwing up ideas I think, and just throwing everything into the ring and then just seeing what settles.</p><p><strong>HM</strong> Liz, these development goals were agreed over a decade ago now. So why look at them again? Is it that we've achieved them all or it is just that they're not relevant?</p><p><strong>LF</strong> It's not that the problems aren't the same; there's just like panic – what do we do after 2015? MDGs have been seen to galvanise action so it's almost like we need something else to galvanise action. And I think how the MDGs were framed, that's not relevant now. There's still lots of relevant problems but it's how these goals are framed and the big issue is are they universal? And if you're bringing in a sustainable development element to this, and there's a working group currently trying to come up with some sustainable development goals, then it's got to be universal because if you're going to deal with environmental issues this is going to impact every country, global north/global south. So I think that's where the thinking is coming from.</p><p><strong>HM</strong> Okay, Liz, well thanks for that. And we'll hear more from you later. So of course what we'll do is we'll hear over the course of this podcast three big ideas about where we might go in the future and let's go to the first of those. As I say Barbara Crowther is the director of policy and public affairs at the Fairtrade Foundation, and Barbara you've had very specific ideas about the targets, tell us a little bit about that.</p><p><strong>BC</strong> Well I think we've had millennium development goals and I think a lot of the focus was really on those measures of halving extreme poverty as measured by the dollar twenty five a day. And I think we need to move on from that framing now to what Liz was talking about which is a universal of what we call sustainable development goals. So what does sustainable development look like both north and south? So yes poverty is part of that picture but it's also about how do we deliver the advances whilst operating within the safe ecological boundaries and limits that we have? So how do we deliver human wellbeing and ecological security for everyone? If you take an example you could say it's not just about increasing the yield of a smallholder farmer it's about whether the percentage of farmers that are practicing sustainable farming, managing water, managing their resources, having access to land and actually earning a livelihood and being resilient to economic and ecological shocks. It's about how can you make sure that development results in people being able to invest in low carbon technology, for example. In Fairtrade, for example, we've seen how equitable, sustainable trade means that farmers have been able to invest themselves in solar powered energy for their villages; so they're increasing their services but they're doing it on the basis of sustainable consumption at this end, promoting a market amongst consumers for purchasing and living sustainably, reducing food waste, buying into ecological products and then delivering sustainability at the other end.</p><p><strong>HM</strong> Give me an example of a way that you can specifically measure a target in activity like that?</p><p><strong>BC</strong> There's all sorts of quirky things that you could do so in Rwanda, for example, as a result of building a sustainable coffee production base the number of hairdressers in local villages have gone up. So it's how far is trade delivering small scale enterprise and creating jobs and equitable growth. It could be about what proportion of people are actually accessing low carbon technology, what percentage of smallholder farmers have access to climate adaptation support, for example. Those might be some of the types of indicator that we could be considering.</p><p><strong>HM</strong> What was missing before? Is that we didn't have the right targets or were we just not measuring them properly, were they being reached?</p><p><strong>BC</strong> If you take food as an example the targets were very much about ending extreme hunger, halving the number of people experiencing extreme hunger, but didn't take into consideration the disparities in people's access to food or, for example, the proportion of food that is simply going to waste. About a third of the food in developed economies is going to waste. And, at the same time, we're pushing towards cheaper and cheaper food and then that's making it a disposal commodity. So actually there's something which is about how do we manage food consumption in the north and deliver sustainable fairly traded food; and then how do we deliver sustainably produced food amongst farmers? So what proportion of farmers are earning a sustainable livelihood would be a good indicator.</p><p><strong>MH</strong> Alex Cobham, let me bring you in there because of course we have to have targets but as Barbara was saying they can bring a complication all on their own.</p><p><strong>AC</strong> Barbara's idea is very interesting not least because of the data that would be required in order to track through, for example, the amount of different types of resources being used in competing ways of farming. Having that data on a consistent basis would really allow you to see much more clearly, both as a consumer and as a policymaker the impact of going down different roads. And I think that would really start to focus us on how far away we are from sustainable agriculture and which direction can take us towards that. So I think it's a great idea.</p><p><strong>HM</strong> What has been the deficiency of the targeting up to now?</p><p><strong>AC</strong> Where to begin?</p><p><strong>HM</strong> We only have 35 minutes, but do what you can!</p><p><strong>AC</strong> Broadly the millennium development goals partly because they're a creature of their time, the discussions in 2000 are very different to the type of discussions that we've had since, particularly at Copenhagen around climate change, but there just wasn't a focus on sustainability in the way that there is now through most of development thinking. So these types of ideas would have been raised by some people within the conversation but they just wouldn't have been central. And that's what we see in the MDGs, they're largely about meeting absolute need today with very little thought for the implications of that in terms of the planet's sustainability.</p><p><strong>BC</strong> And if you take the millennium development goal number seven which was the one that was seen as being the one that came closest to an environmental framework that's one of the ones that is the most off track – I think only 10% of the low level indicators have actually been met. So yes there was some increase in people's access to water, the sanitation target's way off, but really importantly biodiversity loss, which was one of the indicators there, we've gone backwards in the last ten years.</p><p><strong>HM</strong> Musimbi Kanyoro in New York, on this issue of targeting if we had to revisit that and how it's done what would you tell them?</p><p><strong>MK</strong> I would tell them that what failed us in the whole of the last MDG was we focused a lot on issues. But what we learnt that for every one of the issues that we dealt with when women are not considered to be the top priority we don't make progress on those issues. So I would really say one of the things that is really important is to have an independent MDG, or whatever we shall call it, that looks on gender equality. Because we talk of agriculture, we're going to look and see that actually in many developing countries 70% of the people in agriculture are women. And if there is no gender equality that looks at what they are contributing to that level we're still not going to be able to sustain what is happening in agriculture. We look at the question of security of violence, and we see that the most impacted people in wars, in areas of conflict etc are women. And when we don't look at that we'll just find that once again we are dancing in the place. And one of the MDGs that really did not meet its target is the MDG on sexual and reproductive health.</p><p><strong>HM</strong> Dr Kanyoro we'll talk more about the specific of the goals that refer to gender in just a moment. But just talking about targeting, and Liz can I just bring you in here: what's the feeling about the targeting process as to whether or not it needs a review, what are you hearing?</p><p><strong>LF</strong> Well, I think it was quite interesting that just listening to what everyone's been saying and the targeting's an issue, but right now it just seems from certainly civil society that the issue of funding and economics seems to be more in people's head than targeting. Everyone assumes or would like to see, most people I've spoken to, would like to see a universal set of goals and whatever your particular issue is you'd want sanitation having a target, and you'd want sexual and reproductive rights to have a target – you'd have all these things in. But the big thing that's coming out is calls for restructuring of the financial institutions; so restructuring the IMF, restructuring the World Bank to put funding in place that gives countries ownership over what they do with their funds. And this whole idea of some kind of paradigm shift in thinking we can have a new set of targets in universal goals, but if there isn't this kind of move to give governments easier access and more power over finances then nothing is going to be achieved in the same way. And what's been missed over the last 13 years those sort of things are going to be missed again. So it was quite interesting just hearing that seems to be the message that's coming from civil society.</p><p><strong>HM</strong> Okay. I'm going to go back to Dr Musimbi Kanyoro there in New York because she was talking about the gender element of the goals, and of course some say that improving the lives of women would impact on all of the development goals across the board. But of course there is that goal three from the last set promoting gender equality and empowering women; give me your sense of what's happened in the past ten years.</p><p><strong>MK</strong> I think they need to raise the bar because one of the things that it did is that it did create a consciousness so that there are many actors now that can talk about gender equality. But it also, by increasing the visibility, it also has increased a kind of resistant bug that we see continuing to come on especially from people that think that this MDG is not in line with their culture or their religious beliefs. And if we do not continue very, very strongly on that and also create targets for it because we're talking more than 50% of the global population that we want to address, then again we won't be able to make the progress that we need to do.</p><p>And for me it also involves investing a sufficient amount of resources, financial and otherwise, that will go on to translate this gender equality into empowerment of actual women as individuals but also as communities.</p><p><strong>HM</strong> Is it a hard sell persuading people that the gender element is important across the board; that it shouldn't just be looked at in isolation that it really impinges on everything?</p><p><strong>MK</strong> I think currently because now we have a number of researches that have been done, including a research by the World Bank, that shows what you gain by investing in women, but also the research that had been done by independent institutions, so there is evidence, there is data. And we can rise beyond just speaking, just words about women. But the fear is not the fear that women will be included rather it is the subordination of women that is inherent in the patriarchal systems that exist all over the world.</p><p><strong>HM</strong> So as we think about what goals we'll have going forward what is it that you're hoping for; what would success look like?</p><p><strong>MK</strong> Success for me would look like really investments; investment of money, of resources, of talents into women. Investing in women-led initiatives, investing in women's organisations that are currently really pushing the envelope on laws and policies being changed and cultural norms being changed in places. Those that are using a human rights and justice framework to look at what is happening in their communities; looking at the issues of security, food; looking at the issues of economics, looking at the issues of inclusion in politics – really investing and really trusting that they are going to be the ones that challenge their own governments to make a move in those particular areas.</p><p><strong>HM</strong> And, Barbara, let me quickly bring you in there – how do we raise the status, if you like, of the gender issue across the board?</p><p><strong>BC</strong> First of all, I think it is imperative that we do do so. One of the issues around the millennium goals is that I think it was a very top down process and I think we've already seen in the conversations that have been going on for the last year or two that it's been a bit more of a bottom up process. So I think first of all it's about the inclusion of women in the translation of any new set of goals in its implementation at a national, at a local level and the empowerment of women through that process.</p><p>We've certainly seen that for every pound you invest in women whether that's in women's entrepreneurship or whether that's women's access to agricultural, technical know-how you actually get a really, really good return on that investment. So I think it would be a really sensible investment to make.</p><p><strong>HM</strong> Alex Cobham, are we missing a trick?</p><p><strong>AC</strong> I don't think so. People talk about in the MDGs that the greater success was goal 1A the reduction of people living in absolute income poverty – I think that's nonsense on stilts. Partly because a lot of what happened would have happened anyway and we successfully watered down the actual quantitative meaning of that goal. So even by the time it was set, China had already ensured that East Asia had met their goal for 2015.</p><p><strong>HM</strong> So it was illusory you think?</p><p><strong>AC</strong> I think it drew the attention in a way that's actually not very helpful if we're looking back and thinking about what worked. In fact what I'd say is the greater success of the MDGs is MDG three. It wasn't so much that we've seen enormous changes in the ratios of girls and boys going to school it was the setting of a norm that gender equality was something that every society everywhere ought to be aiming for. And not only in terms of who goes to primary school but actually much more broadly. The way that norm was understood and translated politically and socially and culturally was, I think, much more important than any specific changes that happened in terms of, let's say, investment in education. Now you could say we had that in the last set so why do we need it in post-2015? I think the answer is in that question – if you step back now I think it risks sending a message that this is no longer a priority, no longer something that should be seen as a norm perhaps to the same extent.</p><p><strong>HM</strong> Liz in New York, what's your take on this?</p><p><strong>LF</strong> I think that anyone that you would speak to here from civil society, from UN women would say there has been some progress. But there's still so much work to do. And I think that bears out when you speak to, say, Uganda. You go to a rural area of Uganda and you speak to women there and you see what's happened. And some things have shifted so you have got more girls going to school up until primary school, but then you've got a big issue of child marriage; so OK families might be happy for the child to go to school until they're 12 but after that, no. So you've got to break down those sorts of barriers afterwards.</p><p>I think everyone knows that regardless of what you think about any goals or targets having gender equality as a goal and having indicators and how it's treaded through just reminds people of nothing else that you need to attack with these issues. And it has been the one that hasn't properly been achieved. And there have been lots of ideas about gender mainstreaming so that everything that you do, every kind of UN policy makes sure there's a certain number of women in it. It all seems to come down to a shift in power and I know, Barbara, at a round table I think you touched on this and it's where does the power lie and I think any new goals or indicators need to indicate that the power needs to shift so men still aren't in charge, women really need to seize power and move for anything to really change.</p><p><strong>HM</strong> I want to bring Barbara in in just a moment, but in the spring you were in New York for a meeting on women's rights – what's the thinking there and what's the evaluation there of where they are so far and where they need to go?</p><p><strong>LF</strong> In March there was a commission on the status of women which was looking specifically at violence against women and eliminating violence against women. And it was quite worrying in certain governments, certain groups were lobbying hard to effectively roll back the rights that women have worked so hard to actually achieve. And there was a massive fight to actually get an actual outcome document to vow to eliminate violence against women and girls. And it just seemed like two weeks of intense discussions to move a centimetre forward almost and it was quite shocking to see that there was this amazing opposition and to actually see it in all its glory. And you've got this real kind of sexual reproductive health and rights, giving women rights over their body; so access to family planning, abortion in this kind of context it has such stiff opposition and I think that's going to be a continuing challenge.</p><p><strong>MK</strong> Women's rights movements who are here and who were here in March really insist that equality and human dignity has to take precedence over customs and traditions. And they are working towards that and it doesn't matter whether you come from a religious background or whether you come from a cultural background that has done certain things for a long time, they are not right to do now. And that's what we want to happen.</p><p><strong>HM</strong> And Barbara?</p><p><strong>BC</strong> This issue of power is absolutely critical to the whole of the framework I think so whether you're looking at it from the point of view of access to climate adaptation, whether you're looking at it from a gender point of view there is this huge issue. So if you're a cocoa farmer today in West Africa you're earning probably between 3% and 6% of the value of a chocolate bar compared to 18% in the 1980s. So whilst there's been this progress in people investing in sustainable agriculture actually the value is not shifting and the control of that trade has become incredibly concentrated and as a result millions of small scale farmers are relatively powerless. And so we have to address power and the big elephant in the room really is this shift of power that's going on at the moment from the state and the public sector into the private sector. We work with a lot of businesses, I'm absolutely in favour of using trade as a tool for development, of getting business to play its role, but we need to make sure that goes alongside accountable frameworks that those businesses have to then be made accountable for the social and environmental and economic impacts and contribute into and doing business in a better way that delivers more value back to developing countries.</p><p><strong>HM</strong> Barbara, thank you. You mentioned the economic impact and I sense we're going to get into that in just a moment because as I say we're looking at three big ideas; we've talked about targeting, we've talked about the gender issue. Finally in this edition let's here from Alex Cobham he's, as I said, the research fellow at the Centre for Global Development. And you have big ideas about income equality and inequality.</p><p><strong>AC</strong> Well let me build up to that, Hugh. I'm going to start with a big problem – the easiest thing to do for rich countries is to set targets for poor countries. And I think at the risk of being marginally unfair that's pretty much where the MDGs come from and why they look like they do. So there's two things that we ought to turn around in that dynamic. The first one is that the post-2015 framework must include binding targets for rich countries aid donor countries themselves. And that takes us down a set of roads: one is dealing much more comprehensively with questions of sustainability and environmental impact which if, in a sense, if you limit goals to poorer countries only of course you're not getting anywhere near a planetary solution.</p><p>So what I propose is that rather than looking for a post-2015 agreement that sets the goals and targets for every country instead we follow up on … the argument I was making about gender is important in the MDGs that it was the norm setting that mattered rather than the specific target, we look at setting areas in which the norm says \"there should be a target\" and then we devolve to national political processes the setting of that actual target.</p><p>So let's take the example of income inequality as you mentioned. The high level panel report co-chaired by David Cameron said that income inequality was too political for there to be a target as if somehow telling a set of lower income countries that they must have targets on policy, on sustainability, on child mortality as if that's not political, as if that's not setting priorities and budgets and so on. So that question of it being political I think is a difficult one. But if we go with what the high level panel says there what it means is not, I think, that therefore we shouldn't talk about inequality it's that there should be a political process around inequality. Now think, for a moment, how powerful could it be if we had rippling across the world in each country involved the question being asked in democratic processes what is the type of inequality that is acceptable, what's an acceptable inequality of child mortality say between the richest and poorest?</p><p><strong>HM</strong> That's sounds fine but what is the political reality of that because if you close the income gap you almost inevitably take money from the rich, are they really going to agree to that?</p><p><strong>AC</strong> Every country in the world, every society in the world is effectively day to day choosing what it considers the acceptable level of income inequality, that's not going to be the same in every society and we can see that looking across rich countries there are great variance, great differences. But the one thing we can be sure of is if we take it off the table, if we say this is not a fit subject to discuss the tendency is for inequality to rise.</p><p><strong>HM</strong> How do you persuade rich countries that they should almost cede control of the process in that way because at the moment they do, pretty much, have control of the process?</p><p><strong>AC</strong> I think it's a question of how they see development. If donor countries are going to hold fast this idea that really they ought to be able to set priorities for other countries, which I think is indefensible when it's out in the open like that, then I think we have a problem. But I think once you confront that idea and you ask what is it that we're looking for here most people involved would say an important element of this is the political empowerment of people living in developing countries. And that means not saying: \"Here are the targets, let's see if your government meets them.\" It means saying: \"Here are some areas, what targets do you want to set for your government in each of these areas?\"</p><p><strong>HM</strong> Musimbi in New York do you think that that is realistic, I mean it's obviously very desirable to change the balance of power in these things but is it realistic that it might happen easily or happen soon?</p><p><strong>MK</strong> It's a good thing to talk about but we don't know anywhere in history where people have given up power easily by themselves. Because people do count what is in it for them. And this is the same when we are talking about the public/private cooperation that we have now and emphasising business it's the same. There's power there, there's the power of money, there's the power of having to make profit that will have to be there. And even when you take countries by themselves and say OK you're going to tell the countries to set their own limitations, again even within the countries women still have limited access to power and responsibilities in the public sphere due to the prevailing inequality at the family level, inequality at the society level; so either way the only way we'll be able to balance power is if we don't put the recognition just in the governments but really be able to see the movements, people's movements, indigenous movements, women's movements that actually do name power as an issue.</p><p><strong>AC</strong> Spot on. But the question of involving a political discussion let's take gender, think about gender inequality – it's true if we have these discussions within countries that have gender inequality, and let's not forget that rich countries actually have less female representation in parliament than a lot of developing countries. But anyway, if we have those discussions it's true that we're doing it within an unequal context but which country, which government wants to be the one which globally has set the lowest, the weakest possible target out of all countries on gender inequality, or on the inequality between the top 10% and the bottom 40% by income, let's say. I think once you open this process up you have a set of international pressures as well as domestic ones which ultimately may point in a good direction. Certainly I would say better than if we pretend there's no politics involved here, that we can set this all internationally and not ask these questions domestically.</p><p><strong>HM</strong> Barbara, what do you think how do we change this balance of power?</p><p><strong>BC</strong> I think the tectonic plates are shifting already and we need to get wise to that. So the emerging economies are already shifting the balance of power in lots of ways. I think the broad principle of saying how do we create the political processes and empower ordinary people to hold their own governments accountable, to set the right frameworks for how and where business is involved in the delivery of these kind of goals is absolutely spot on. And I think it would raise some really interesting debates. So it's not just jobs but it's what is the disparity between any country's national minimum wage, which in most developing countries you have to have three or four jobs at that wage to be able to survive.</p><p><strong>HM</strong> Think about this: how do we factor in the fact that a lot of governments might be given more authority to take more local decisions and have local targets but they won't be democratic so are they really reflecting the targets that the people might want?</p><p><strong>AC</strong> But I think if you have no discussion around appropriate levels of inequality, whether that's economic inequality or inequality between ethnolinguistic groups let's say or by gender then the absence of that discussion facilitates a set of policies that are more likely to exacerbate that inequality. What I'm suggesting here is that by forcing this on to the agenda at least you require that discussion to happen. Now governments can then be good or bad, they can meet targets or not, they can agree good targets or not but at least that process has begun, there's been a discussion, you've allowed people, to some extent, to air their views. And I think from then you have a sense that the targets that are set are much more likely to be met.</p><p><strong>HM</strong> Okay. Let's go back to Liz Ford our deputy editor for Global development, she's in our New York studio, Liz, you've been hearing all that, does this reflect some of what you've been hearing in New York as well as they discuss what their next steps?</p><p><strong>LF </strong>Obviously there's more than 1,000 representatives of civil society here who are lobbying their case and Ban Ki-moon has talked about the importance of civil society groups in meeting any kind of set of goals or MDGs, but also anything that comes afterwards. A recent report warns that a lot of civil society groups are finding it very hard to operate in their own countries. So it ties into the power thing so even if you shift responsibility to governments, as you said, if you haven't got a government that's receptive to being questioned or to being pushed then you're going to run up against difficulties.</p><p>It's quite interesting just to hear how tricky the funding issue is going to be and how people are really pushing for these things. And also trying to understand about how the human rights frame is actually going to work because we've got all these declarations on the table that have been there for years, so in a sense someone was saying to me do we need another set of goals because in theory we have all this UN framework here so why aren't we just looking at that and using it. So I think how those things are going to be teased out will be the challenge. And I think a lot of NGOs will be very pleased if there is an announcement about accelerating progress on the MDGs. But in a sense it feels a little bit like it's almost had its day and everyone's looking at post-2015 and how we get the new lot. And in a sense how important is it for us to meet those MDG targets now?</p><p><strong>HM</strong> So, Liz, just before we go a lot of discussion is going on there, what should we be looking out for next; what's the next big issue?</p><p><strong>LF</strong> This is obviously an interesting time whatever comes out of the next two days we're expecting an outcome document committing the UN to move on, accelerate and all those sort of things. But I think the next two years are going to be … in a sense 2013 is an important year, it's party year, it's blue skies year, it's throw everything in – but the next two years is when it gets really sort of down and dirty about trying to come up with what are these new set of goals going to look like. And I think what's going to be interesting is next year the open working group on the sustainable development goals report back, and I think that really could put the cat amongst the pigeons because they're going to come back with suggestions about environmental sustainability and the word \"environmental\" will just freak a lot of governments out I imagine.</p><p><strong>HM</strong> Dr Musimbi Kanyoro what should we be looking out for from your point of view?</p><p><strong>MK</strong> I always take the stand that for anything that we want to do we have to begin from the people themselves that are going to experience it. If we're going to talk about poverty, poverty has a face to it. And so what I've been observing of late is what is happening in regions, what is happening in countries, even in times of their own people getting more voice to challenge the systems under which they exist, like we've seen in the Middle East; or new constitutions that are beginning actually to discuss the issue of democratising constitutions in countries. Egypt is working on a new constitution. Kenya, two years ago, passed a new constitution that has got many opportunities for men and women to work together. And then this whole big debate about the role of men in development. I think that the next focus should not only be on what happens in gender equality in regards to women actually but the responsibilities also that men and governments that have been in the past considered conservative can do, or are doing.</p><p><strong>HM</strong> Thank you. Barbara Crowther, what next?</p><p><strong>BC</strong> The big question is how far this framework is going to be a MDG with a few add-ons or whether it is actually going to try and come up with a slightly more transformative framework. I think Liz is right about the working group on inclusive sustainable development goals. I think there are real questions about how far we link other processes in such as if we're talking about leveraging the power of the private sector how do we hardwire in the number of businesses that are in compliance with the new UN guiding principles on Business and Human Rights, for example.</p><p>And then financing is obviously going to remain a really big issue; where does the money come from for investment. And new forms of investment; it was good to see tax included in the high level panel amongst their recommendations. But I think the real challenge is going to be how far does that high level panel report form the basis of moving forward; or will some of the slightly more radical ideas get filtered back out and we end up with just a slight tweak of the existing framework which would be an opportunity missed if that happened.</p><p><strong>HM</strong> OK. And last with the crystal ball, Alex Cobham?</p><p><strong>AC</strong> OK. So two things: one is we've heard from Liz and Musimbi particularly about problems of governments being unresponsive to civil society. If we go down the MDG road in effect we'll pretend that that doesn't matter and we'll have a set of goals that can be met effectively by a dictatorship. I don't think we should do that, I don't think we're going to do that. So questions around effective political participation will become more prominent.</p><p>The other aspect just to pick up is on illicit financial flows where the high level panel has recommended there be a target. I think we're going to see some really exciting discussions over what an appropriate target would be to combat tax evasion, tax avoidance related flows of money laundering, and I'm hoping CGD plays a role in that.</p><p><strong>HM</strong> OK well things to look forward to in the short term and the long term too. But that's about all we have time for on this podcast. My thanks to Liz Ford in New York, and all of our big thinkers who were Alex Cobham, Dr Musimbi Kanyoro and Barbara Crowther. If you want to join the discussion you can find us at theguardian.com/globaldevelopment. My name's Hugh Muir. The producer is Matt Hill. Thank you for listening.</p>","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Environment/Pix/columnists/2013/5/14/1368545294465/MDG--Millennium-Developme-003.jpg"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2013/oct/02/global-development-podcast-2015-transcript","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/global-development/2013/oct/02/global-development-podcast-2015-transcript","sectionName":"Global development"},{"webTitle":"Guardian Weekly letters, 4 October 2013","webPublicationDate":"2013-10-01T11:49:00Z","sectionId":"global","id":"global/2013/oct/01/guardian-weekly-letters-4-october","fields":{"body":"<h2><strong>A perfect storm brewing</strong></h2><p>My alarm bells rang in deafening tones after reading four features in the 20 September issue (<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2013/sep/23/ttwitter-ipo-loan-thanksgiving-flotation\" title=\"\">Twitter eyes stock market</a>; <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/sep/14/californian-capitalism-can-teach-britain\" title=\"\">California is the face of the new economy</a>; <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/sep/04/blunders-government-king-crewe-review\" title=\"\">How not to do it</a>; and <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/science/2013/sep/11/astronomer-royal-global-warming-lord-rees\" title=\"\">Geoengineering \"last resort\" to stop global warming</a>). Interface all four and a recipe for disaster emerges.</p><p>The disconnect of almost all world political leaders from science and technology is well documented. Peter Wilby's critique of The Blunders of our Governments makes an equally compelling case for what we have all long suspected: the total lack of awareness on the part of our ruling regimes regarding the needs, desires and day-to-day existential demands of most of their electorate – or should that read \"subjects?\"</p><p>Will Hutton's conclusion that the current Californian \"Silicon Valley\" example is one we should emulate is surely based on an idealistic view of world society: one where venture capitalism collaborates with information technology/social media and wise, benevolent government, in order to bring about a new version of the industrial revolution, but this time with fewer or no casualties.</p><p>I'm sorry, Will. The momentum of short-term exploitation of people and resources, which exemplifies the present model of capitalism in vogue world-wide, will not easily be stopped, or even slowed down, simply by asking Apple to slap on a few more human-friendly apps or seeding clouds with seawater. It will require a much more radical reappraisal of our core values and methods of choosing our leaders to achieve the necessary turnaround. We can only hope we're not already too late to make the change.<br /><strong>Noel Bird</strong><br />Boreen Point, Queensland, Australia</p><p></p><p>• In <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/science/2013/sep/11/astronomer-royal-global-warming-lord-rees\" title=\"\">Alok Jha's article about geoengineering (20 September)</a>, the astronomer royal Lord Rees appropriately describes such action as \"an utter political nightmare\". Two of the strategies under consideration are cloud seeding and the injection of sulphate particles into the upper atmosphere, in both cases with the intention of reducing the solar radiation reaching the earth. However, such an approach would mean that both thermal and photovoltaic solar panels would work less efficiently, thereby increasing the demand on carbon-based energy sources. Thus these approaches might prove to be self-defeating.</p><p>As Lord Rees says, the time to start decarbonising the world's power generation is now.<br /><strong>Roger Browne</strong><br />Alexandra, New Zealand</p><h2><strong>Keep Kenya's aquifers safe</strong></h2><p>The discovery of vast aquifers in the arid areas of north-west Kenya (<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2013/sep/11/kenya-water-discovery-drought-relief\" title=\"\">20&nbsp;September</a>) is good news indeed as it has the potential to transform the livelihoods of the people in the area. I worry, though, about our exploitation of this valuable resource and suspect that it will end up being plundered rather than used carefully and sustainably.</p><p>The first steps to take would be a) accurately determining the recharge source(s); b) finding out the rate of recharge; and c) aggressively protecting the recharge watershed. Collectively, our history of resource exploitation suggests that this will not happen and opportunists will already be plotting how vast sums of money can be made from the discovery.<br /><strong>Stuart Williams</strong><br />Kampala, Uganda</p><h2><strong>Migration policy myopia</strong></h2><p>Re: <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2013/sep/13/migration-improve-life-people-poor-countries\" title=\"\">Migration debate \"needs to change focus\" </a>(20 September), there's a blind spot in the global debate over migration and that's exactly the way the new Australian government likes it. By only communicating select information about the arrival of asylum seekers in its waters, they use this blind spot to their advantage. The blind can only lead the blind.</p><p>Never mind the International Organisation for Migration report mentioned in the article, which states that migrants between poor countries fare poorly and are unlikely to feel optimistic about their lives. Never mind that the burden of refugee crises across the globe already fall on disadvantaged nations. Never mind that Australia is the envy not only of poor nations, but rich ones as well.</p><p>Ignore these realities and the border between the rich and poor – the sovereign border – will be secured.<br /><strong>Eddie Tikoft</strong><br />Perth, Western Australia</p><h2><strong>Keep Greens off the fringe</strong></h2><p>At last a mention of the UK's Green party in the Guardian Weekly (UK News in brief, 20 September). And a clue as to the inclusion of the tiny article? The Green party leader is a former Guardian Weekly editor.</p><p>Why the almost total lack of coverage of any other than the major parties? Even the current percentage of the vote smaller parties receive in UK elections is a mystery to me.</p><p>Here in Australia the Greens are a much stronger political force and its players and policies command a high profile in the media, albeit often a negative one in the Murdoch-dominated press. However, if coverage of Green party policies in the broader British press is as poor as that in the GW, then surely the UK Green party is doomed to remain on&nbsp;the fringe.<br /><strong>Gabby Whitworth</strong><br />Tasmania, Australia</p><h2><strong>IOC must confront Russia</strong></h2><p>Owen Gibson's critique of the new IOC president, Thomas Bach (<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/sep/13/fencing-gold-olympics-chief-thomas-bach\" title=\"\">September 20</a>), was a welcome change from the usual worshipful treatment of all things and all men Olympic.</p><p>However, Gibson omitted one significant act reported in other media.</p><p>After Bach had received the congratulatory phone call from President Putin, he \"joked\" to reporters that they had not discussed Russia's anti-gay law. To trivialise this issue, one of the biggest challenges facing the Olympic industry since the bribery scandals, is more than just a bad beginning to Bach's presidency. It's one more indication of the IOC's moral bankruptcy.<br /><strong>Helen Jefferson Lenskyj</strong><br />Toronto, Ontario, Canada</p><h2><strong>Much ado about doing</strong></h2><p>I found your banner headline Merkel's mantra: \"<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/sep/10/german-elections-2013-europe-angela-merkel\" title=\"\">Do as we do\"</a> (13 September) very interesting. Far from only being the mantra of Germany's Angela Merkel, it is probably one of the world's most used and the cause of the vast majority of wars. If only we could all adopt a philosophy based on the Indian expression \"<em>paach angulia bara bara nahin</em>\", meaning that on one hand the fingers are all different but they work very well together.<br /><strong>David Murray</strong><br />Montbrun-Bocage, France</p><p></p><p>• An old saying, but still a valid one: He who pays the piper calls the tune.<br /><strong>Bronwyn Sherman</strong><br />Tutukaka, New Zealand</p><h2>Leave family out of women's careers</h2><p>In reference to Rowan Moore's article: <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2013/sep/08/zaha-hadid-serpentine-sackler-profile\" title=\"\">Zaha Hadid: queen of the curve</a> (20 September), we are not aware of any proven relevance of a partner or children to an architect's creativity or career. Indeed in Moore's piece on <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2013/jul/14/richard-rogers-interview-wimbledon-house\" title=\"\">Richard Rogers in July</a> this seems of no real significance. When will the unnecessary noting of a successful women's family life, appearance or fashion be recognised as simply another form of misogyny? Were you just throwing us a curve ball or have you already forgotten your rightful indignation at the similar treatment of Julia Gillard?<br /><strong>Melissa Hamilton</strong><br />Mugnanese, Loc Gioiella, Italy</p><h2><strong>Briefly</strong></h2><p>• Re: Henry Porter, Britons and privacy (<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/sep/07/britons-privacy-not-important\" title=\"\">13 September</a>). It may be that Britons who do understand privacy to be important have also, rightly, always presumed that it has never existed on the internet. But the government that tells us that if we have done nothing wrong we have nothing to fear from exposure also fears its own activities being exposed.</p><p>Our real fears are that the agencies will then misinterpret the information they procure. They did on intercepting Iraqi communications actually referring to the long ago destruction of the country's weapons of mass destruction, and judging by the amount of car parking around NSA and GCHQ offices in Cheltenham, they cannot work out bus timetables. And of course it is those being spied upon who are paying for the spying.<br /><strong>Adrian Betham</strong><br />London, UK</p><p></p><p>• I am an 85-year old male born in England and can honestly say Nancy Blackett, intrepid captain of the sailing dingy \"Amazon\", was the fictional hero who shaped my life. Somehow Kate Mosse (<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/booksblog/2013/aug/24/where-have-all-brave-girls-gone-kate-mosse\" title=\"\">Where have all the brave girls gone?</a> (20 September) must have missed out on the Manchester Guardian's wonderful Arthur Ransome who wrote about the Swallows and Amazons in 12 books, detailing these amazing children from the Lake District. Recently I received pictures of an Arthur Ransome festival held near Henley-on-Thames. My granddaughter and all the girls there wanted to play the part of Nancy Blackett. <br /><strong>Tony Taylor</strong><br />Victoria, British Columbia, Canada</p><p></p><p>• I liked David Shariatmadari's piece on the threat of plastic bank notes (<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/sep/12/security-plastic-banknotes-soul\" title=\"\">20 September</a>). He can rest assured that if he ventures outside the eurozone and Anglo-Saxonia, he'll still find some fabulous paper notes. <br /><strong>Steve Morris</strong><br />Tonbridge, Kent, UK</p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p><em>Please send letters to </em><a href=\"mailto:weekly.letters@guardian.com\" title=\"\"><em>weekly.letters@guardian.com</em></a></p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/global/2013/oct/01/guardian-weekly-letters-4-october","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/global/2013/oct/01/guardian-weekly-letters-4-october","sectionName":"Global"},{"webTitle":"Sen. Ron Wyden: NSA 'repeatedly deceived the American people' | Glenn Greenwald","webPublicationDate":"2013-09-27T11:14:00Z","sectionId":"commentisfree","id":"commentisfree/2013/sep/27/ron-wyden-nsa-systematically-deceived","fields":{"body":"<p><strong>(updated below - Update II [Sat.])</strong></p><p>The Senate Intelligence Committee yesterday <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/sep/26/nsa-surveillance-senate-committee?CMP=twt_gu\">held a hearing</a>, ostensibly to investigate various issues raised about the NSA's activities. What the hearing primarily achieved instead was to underscore what a farce the notion of Congressional oversight over the NSA is. </p><p>In particular, the current chair of the Senate Committee created in the mid-1970s to oversee the intelligence community just so happens to be one of the nation's most steadfast and blind loyalists of and apologists for the National Security State: Dianne Feinstein. For years she has abused her position to shield and defend the NSA and related agencies rather than provide any meaningful oversight over it, which is a primary reason why it has grown into such an out-of-control and totally unaccountable behemoth.</p><p>Underscoring the purpose of yesterday's hearing (and the purpose of Feinstein's Committee more broadly): the witnesses the Committee first heard from were all Obama officials - Director of National Intelligence James Clapper, NSA chief Gen. Keith Alexander, Deputy Attorney James Cole - who vehemently defended every aspect of the NSA. At the conclusion of their testimony, Feinstein announced that it was very, very important to hear from the two non-governmental witnesses the Committee had invited: <a href=\"http://www.emptywheel.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Screen-shot-2013-09-26-at-5.01.04-PM.png\">virulent NSA defender</a> <a href=\"http://www.lawfareblog.com/2013/08/the-nsa-the-washington-post-and-the-administration/\">Ben Wittes</a> of the Brooking Institution and <a href=\"http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424127887323309404578617463152440542.html\">virulent NSA defender Timothy Edgar</a>, a former Obama national security official. Hearing only from dedicated NSA apologists as witnesses: <a href=\"http://www.emptywheel.net/2013/09/26/dianne-feinstein-gives-nsa-apologist-ben-wittes-more-oversight-time-than-ron-wyden/?utm_source=rss&amp;utm_medium=rss&amp;utm_campaign=dianne-feinstein-gives-nsa-apologist-ben-wittes-more-oversight-time-than-ron-wyden\">that's \"oversight\" for Dianne Feinstein</a> and her oversight Committee. </p><p>Democratic Sen. Mark Warner stated the obvious to Gen. Alexander: \"a lot of Americans have lost trust in what you're doing.\" But of course they all spent the entire afternoon blaming Snowden and \"the media\" for this development rather than taking any responsibility themselves. The very idea that meaningful reform of the NSA will come out of this annexed, captured, corrupted Committee is ludicrous on its face.</p><p>But there are two members of that Committee who actually do take seriously its oversight mandate: Democrats Ron Wyden and Mark Udall. Those two <a href=\"http://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/16/us/politics/democratic-senators-warn-about-use-of-patriot-act.html?_r=0\">spent years publicly winking and hinting that the NSA</a> under President Obama was engaged in all sorts of radical and abusive domestic surveillance (although - despite the <a href=\"http://www.foreignpolicy.com/articles/2013/08/1/breach_or_debate_congress_snowden_prism%20\">absolute immunity protection they enjoy as Senators under the Constitution</a> - they took no action, and instead waited for Edward Snowden (who had no such immunity) to bravely step up and reveal to the American people specifically what these two Senators kept hinting at). </p><p>Wyden spoke yesterday for 6 minutes - part of of it as monologue and part of it questioning Gen. Alexander - and it's really worth watching the video, embedded below. The Oregon Democrat condemned what he called \"the intrusive, constitutionally flawed surveillance system\" the NSA built. About Snowden's whistleblowing, he said that NSA officials should have known from \"a quick read of history, in America, the truth always managed to come out.\" And his primary point was this: \"<strong>the leadership of NSA built an intelligence collection system that repeatedly deceived the American people</strong>.\"</p><p>Indeed, if I had to pick the single most revealing aspect of this entire NSA scandal - and there are many revealing ones about many different realms - it would be that James Clapper <a href=\"http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/post-politics/wp/2013/06/11/sen-wyden-clapper-didnt-give-straight-answer-on-nsa-programs/\">lied to the faces of the Senate Intelligence Committee about core NSA matters</a>, and not only was he not prosecuted <a href=\"http://codes.lp.findlaw.com/uscode/18/I/47/1001\">for that felony</a>, but he did not even lose his job, and continues to be treated with great reverence by the very Committee which he deliberately deceived. That one fact tells you all you need to know about how official Washington functions.</p><figure class=\"element element-video\" data-canonical-url=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uF40mZbrd7I\">  <iframe width=\"460\" height=\"259\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/uF40mZbrd7I?wmode=opaque&feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen>  </iframe></figure><h2>Related issues</h2><p>This is <a href=\"http://www.nytimes.com/2013/09/27/opinion/have-a-nice-day-nsa.html?hp\">an insightful, and quite hilarious, Op-ed</a> in the New York Times this morning by the Brazilian journalist Vanessa Barbara about how Brazilians are using humor to mock and subvert the NSA's surveillance schemes.</p><p>Finally, in case there are any people left who thought that exploiting Terrorism and fear-mongering over it for power was a unique by-product of the Bush era (and really: could there <a href=\"http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/2chambers/post/harry-reid-rand-paul-spar-over-patriot-act-on-senate-floor/2011/05/25/AGcgWRBH_blog.html\">really be any people left who believe that at this point?</a>), <a href=\"http://thehill.com/blogs/hillicon-valley/technology/324499-nsa-chief-pleads-for-publics-help-as-congress-eyes-restrictions#ixzz2g5cAVyzd\">Gen. Alexander this week</a> \"warned that if Congress hampers the NSA's ability to gather information, it could allow for terrorist attacks in the United States similar to last week's massacre in a mall in Nairobi, Kenya\", while Feinstein's deputy Chair, GOP Sen. Saxby Chambliss (who revealingly sounds like every Democratic NSA defender I ever hear) said that the recent NSA disclosures \"caused huge damage to the US\" and \"would ultimately claim lives.\"</p><h2>UPDATE</h2><p>Anyone who has any interest in understanding how the US media works: <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/media/media-blog/2013/sep/27/seymour-hersh-obama-nsa-american-media\">please read this article about what Seymour Hersh said in a speech yesterday</a> regarding government-subservient, \"chicken shit\" US journalists. editors and media outlets. It is hard to put into words just how comprehensively accurate his remarks are.</p><h2>UPDATE II [Sat.]</h2><p>On Twitter, Wittes <a href=\"https://twitter.com/benjaminwittes/status/383914571926220800\">objects</a> to my description of him as a \"virulent NSA defender\", saying: \"I am certainly an NSA defender, but curious what I have said that strikes you as 'virulent'. I try to keep virulence out of it.\" It's a fair point, and was a bad word choice on my part. I meant to convey that he's steadfast, relentless and intense in his defense of the NSA - I probably was thinking of \"vehement\". \"Virulent\" connotes poisonous or spiteful rhetoric and Wittes generally avoids that. In my view, he's certainly a hard-core apologist for NSA abuses and more generally a highly loyal US government defender, but he usually employs a Brookings-type civil tone when engaging in all that.</p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/sep/27/ron-wyden-nsa-systematically-deceived","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/commentisfree/2013/sep/27/ron-wyden-nsa-systematically-deceived","sectionName":"Comment is free"},{"webTitle":"Today's media stories from the papers","webPublicationDate":"2013-09-26T08:44:55Z","sectionId":"media","id":"media/2013/sep/26/media-briefing-thursday-26-september","fields":{"body":"<h2>Top eight stories on <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media\">MediaGuardian</a></h2><figure data-media-id='gu-image-418304626'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Media/Pix/pictures/2013/9/18/1379522217797/John-Whittingdale-008.jpg' alt='John Whittingdale' width='460' height='276' class='gu-image'/><figcaption></figcaption></figure><p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2013/sep/26/google-mps-music-film-piracy\">Google attacked by MPs over failure to curb music and film piracy</a><br /> Company accused of 'derisory' attempts to stop many illegal downloads amid concerns over level of influence in coalition</p><p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/media/2013/sep/26/wpp-martin-sorrell-richard-desmond-group-m\">WPP chief denies its media buying arm bullies broadcasters</a><br /> Sir Martin Sorrell responds to claim by Richard Desmond that Group M's power means broadcasters feel forced to work with it</p><p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/media/2013/sep/25/bbc-uk-top-source-news-ofcom\">BBC rated UK's top source for news</a><br /> Ofcom report shows television is the most important platform for news, with 34% of adults turning to BBC1</p><p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/media/2013/sep/25/mark-thompson-bbc-financial-scrutiny\">Thompson: more financial scr